    'body' => 'ereddoch@amaranth.com (Eris Reddoch) said:
:BTW, I was thinking about (2) yesterday.  Stutter a ship in front of a
:planet travelling in orbit at 30kps and turn off the drive. What\'s the
:ship\'s momentum in its current frame of reference? Could be
:anything..depends on what it was when it turned the stutter
:on...right?  So, let\'s say for this example that when it entered the
:system it had 0 momentum with regard to the star. Now you have a 30kps
:KE bomb sitting in front of the planet!

:So much for stutterwarps (or any reactionless drive) eliminating the
:planet killer.  If there is a way to put a ship/object in the path of
:a planet then the planet can provide all the KE you need for a big
:bang.  Well, I guess you could get around even this, but it *is* an
:added complication.

  Yep. These people that keep trying to artificially limit the game
are dreaming. There just going to have to live with it, and try to think
about we\'ll be dealing with these problems in the future. Heck, that\'s
what s/f is _about_.

   Players are *always* going to find ways to ruin the referees day.
It\'s much better to just keep the game simple and assume that Things
Happen and have a rational system set up to deal with the potential
problem. Trying to drop a PB? Have a patrol cruiser *just happen* to be
in the Right Place at the Right Time. If you\'ve already got the players
used to the idea of an patrol presence, they shouldn\'t object to it.

   Such a game is *much* more fun than a game where the referee says
"hmm, I don\'t like that - sorry you can\'t do it"

   What *is* the difference betwen dropping a rock at 50km/sec and
dropping a rock at .1c? In either case, they are guilty of war crimes
and would be chased to the ends of the universe, in my game.

   Players should be discouraged from doing things like this, but there\'s
better ways than "you can\'t do it".


