    'day' => '20',
    'topic' => ' Alternative FTL',
    'body' => 'On 06/20/96 at 12:54 PM,  Larry Hadley
<lhadley@knet.knet.flemingc.on.ca> said:

>   Stutterwarp would tromp all over any drive that requires
>acceleration. It doesn\'t accellerate, it just moves. So it can change
>direction instantaneously and literally stop on a dime.

As specified in 2300 and FFS you are right.  <g> However, if you
require several seconds to bring the sutter up to speed or to actually
turn it off, say for mechanical reasons, then it will have very fast
pseudo-acceration and psuedo-decelleration.  Then throw in a limit on
the speed that you can slew the direction of the stutterwarp dirve,
say because it needs to be firmly secured to a framework in the hull
you can only change direction by 10 degrees per second, and it takes
18 seconds to reverse direction.
 
Would it still run rings around reaction and standard thruster plates? 
Sure would!  <g>

Of course, you could further limit the stutters.  They could take
longer to pseudo-accelerate.  The turn rate could be even worse, say
the stutter can\'t turn at all, you\'ve got to rotate the ship by other
means...just how fast can you flip a 2000tonne neddle with gyros?  You
could cap their pseudo-speed at lower k/s by making the number of
jumps per second lower and/or the distance per jump smaller.  

I\'m going to play with making stutterswarps sub-c only (or maybe max
them at low c), and use them in the same game where jump is the
standard FTL.  Stutter would be the standard MDrive, and a backup FTL
if you lose the JDrive or something.  <g> I\'ll see how this plays out.

Oh BTW, how does a Stutterwarp match orbital velocity with a planet? 
Or even worse, how would it match velocity with deep space base?  It\'s
got to have some *real* thrust coming from somewhere!

Eris
