    'body' => '> From: "Stuart L. Dollar" <sdollar@goodnet.com>
> 
> On 21 Jun 96 at 16:30, Timothy Collinson spewed:
> > 
> > Has anyone looked at the nitty gritty differences between the
> > Aslan race of Traveller and the Klingons of Star Trek?
> > 
> I\'m not certain the Klingons have quite the preoccupation with land 
> that the Aslan do.  I can see the "honor" comparisons right off...  
> Actually, the way they\'ve been portrayed in later series, I see 
> almost as many comparisons to the Vargr as the Aslan (as long as you 
> substitute "charisma" for "honor")

Well, first of all, the immediate thing that you probably wouldn\'t know
about the Aslan sans Alien module is the gender division.

Aslan females outnumber Aslan males about 3 to 1.

The females take on a variety of non-combat roles - including all
medical, financial, technical, technical support, educational,
etc, etc, issues.

Aslan males deal almost excusively with leadership, politics and
warfare. According to the skill slisted, Aslan males are
unable to deal with even simple concepts like _money_ without
having a special skill to do so.

The Aslan will often ignore a non-Aslan\'s true gender and refer
to a being using a gender selected on the basis of that being\'s
job or skill set. E.g. a ship\'s captain will always be refered
to with male pronouns, a ship\'s doctor or engineer will always have
female pronouns used for them. This faux pas is probably more common
among males than females, as females get educated at least.

This is very unlike the Klingons, who are all ass-kicking
types apparently. Also, Klingons seem to have a more 
"human" sex ratio - men do everything, with the occassional
female character so the producers can throw a pair of breasts
onscreen. (ST and all its offspring still have the most awful
females roles.)

> On the other hand, if you think about it, the way Klingons have been 
> portrayed in Star Trek is inconsistent.  
> 
> In the original Star Trek, they were cardboard cutout villains...no 
> depth of character whatsoever, no explanation of motives...  Only 
> goal was to kill men in red uniforms, and be killed by bridge crew of 
> the Enterpoop...

Isn\'t this what both the Aslan and the Vargr serve to do in Traveller? ;)
 
> In Next Generation, they were portrayed with kind of a Code of 
> Bushido air to them (honor was more important than life, etc).

Yes, this is fairly Aslan.

> Now in DS9, they\'re portrayed almost as a race at war with itself, in 
> a near constant state of turmoil...hence my Vargr comparisons...

I think the idea is that there\'s a big battle for control of the Klingon
race... this is actually not unlike the Aslan, where there are
various competing clans, who fight not only outsiders (Imperium/.
Solomani) but each other. There are distinct, clear clan lines
that can be drawn for the Aslan however, unlike the Vargr, who,from
a human perspective, seem to fight with anyone.

I think the Aslan are motivated somewhat by the Kzin (Kzinti?)
of Larry Niven\'s "Known Space" universe.

If I was to risk being a cynic, I\'d also note that both the Aslan
and the Vargr suffer badly from the "humans in rubber suits"
syndrome. The K\'kree are a bit better, then the Droyne and the
Hivers are probably the most alien aliens. Though none of
the Traveller aliens could be described as "bad head jobs"
(well, not much).

Ethan
