    'body' => '>From: Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca>
>Date: Fri, 28 Jun 1996 03:15:57 -0400 (EDT)
>Subject: MMT Adventure Questions.

>3. How intelligible would writing from before the Long Night be to the 
>Syleans? (i.e., is it like Shakespearean english, or like Gaelic, or what?)

1) Vague and ambiguous:  Writing in what language?  from how long before the
Long Night? just before?

2) How intelligible without applying translation software?  By TL 12 (I
think that\'s Milieu 0), known languages will all be freely translatable by
computers; written forms will be the easiest because most consistent.  So if
the adventurers are in communication with a starship, or if they have a
computer with translation software with that language with them, they will
be able to read it as easily as their native language (which I assume is a
Sylean dialect of English). 

3) While the advent of general literacy has slowed the evolution of language
(at least of grammar; vocabulary changes constantly), the complete
dissemination of audiovisual recording equipment and records, in a culture
that relies on them constantly, will bring such evolution to a near
standstill.  

Between 2 and 3, if the pre-Long Night writing is English, the PCs will have
a pretty easy time reading it.  

- --Glenn

