    'topic' => ' Water World',
    'body' => 'Jamie Young <jamie@tsc.scotnet.co.uk> writes:

> What would the climate of a water-world, say n-86Annn-n, in the habitable
> zone be like?  Would atmospheric currents form latitudinal bands, as on
> Jupiter?

They\'d form latitudinal bands like *Earth*. That\'s what the tradewinds
are. Ditto for the "doldrums".

You\'d also get some mondo storms, because tropical cyclones (hurricanes
& typhoons) wouldn\'t ever run into land masses. They\'d only die out
when they hit *really* cold water.

> Would the oceanographic/atmospheric interaction be unstable
> leading to global ice-ages?

Hmmm. Good question. 

> How would the climate differ between two
> waterworlds, one with a shallow global ocean and one with a deep global
> ocean?

Not sure. I think that what you need to worry about is what the ocean
currents look like, which depends a lot on the sub-surface topography.

> I understand that photdisassociation of atmospheric water would give
> rise to free atmospheric oxygen - it is possible to predict what percentage
> of the resulting atmosphere would be oxygen?

Depends on the starting composition of the planet, among other things.
You\'ll have some nitrogen and inert gases there. The amount of oxygen
depends on how much is left over after oxidizing everything it can get
at. 

In an extreme case you can have enough oxygen to make the place a fire
hazard. But that requires starting with *lots* of water.
 

