> It adds a feeling of continuity to the game that\'s often hard to find.

This is a good idea which I, too, have implemented: continuity of 
characters and objects.  Now, some may say, "Gee, what an amazing 
coincidence that we always seem to run into someone we know no matter 
where we go."  Or, as the local movie critic said of Independence Day, 
"It\'s just a little too coincidental that everyone in the movie meets 
everyone else, even though they are spread over two coasts and have 
disparate jobs.  The computer geek who can crack the alien\'s code just 
happens to have a wife who works for the President, who happens to..."  
[quoted from memory, not verbatim]

In my estimation, however, this sort of thing gives the story (be it a 
book, a movie, or a campaign) MORE believability and likeability.  Sure 
it can be overdone.  But in moderation, use of previously known people 
and objects in future adventures is a good idea.  I strive for a sense of 
familiarity in my campaigns.  Not only do the players enjoy it, but that 
makes the truly strange or unfamiliar seem even more so. 


- -Joe
