    'body' => '>From: Derek Stanley <dstanley@direct.ca>

>Ya but if a starship has a particularly nasty name, "Relentless, etc."  
>It makes the characters want to get away all that much more.  Plus, if 
>keep having them run into "Relentless, whatever" it builds a mystique 
>about that ship and it\'s captian.

One of the Norse sagas involved a ship called the Nameless.  During
construction, the Viking leader said something to the effect of "Why call a
ship Land Ravager when it is destined never to ravage land?  Let us call it
the Nameless and see what it does.  Then we shall give it a new name when it
has proven itself."

The Viking raid turns out to be a complete disaster, with the men getting
separated from their ship, dying of cold and disease instead of in battle,
and running across northern Europe with their tails between their legs.
Near the end of the book, the leader and a few survivors are running,
exhausted and hungry, from pursuers, and they reach the edge of a cliff
looking over the sea.  There below them, being dashed by the surf onto the
rocks, is the wreckage of the Nameless.  The leader says something like, "I
guess a ship lives up to its name, not the other way around."

I\'ve forgotten the name of the saga, having read it in translation when I
was in junior high about 25 years ago.

- --Glenn

