    'id' => undef,
    'body' => 'On Thu, 4 Jul 1996, Eris Reddoch wrote:

> It\'s not the background, exactly.  It\'s not the rules, or how the
> background and rules work together either.  It\'s the FEEL of the game.
> (If I could really explain this, I\'d bottle it.  <g>)

Yeah. "I don\'t know what it is, but I know it when I see it." :)  Being 
unable to put ones finger on what is so great about something you like is 
a rather embarassing situation to be in, but I agree with you.  


> Mine was the original Black Box with 3 little black books that never
> mentioned anything about the Imperium..period.  No adventures!  No
> map!  Totally "roll your own", so we did.

I didn\'t own the 3 little black books until just a few years ago.  In 
going back and collecting all the CT stuff I missed, I\'ve found it best 
to divide my collection into three sub-collections: one collection of those 
things that I want to preserve, which are never touched (I know, how 
anal!  But I live in fear of someday being without an original copy of 
the Traveller rules, thus the redundancy and care); a collection of things 
that I have only one copy of but which I will go ahead and use (ie, 
Group One items, etc.); and a third collection of items which are used 
without overmuch concern for their condition (essentially, multiple 
copies of the stuff in the first collection, which just happens to 
comprise what I see as the core rules (books 1-8, Supplements 1-13, and 
The Traveller Book)).  
Anyway, the point of saying all that was to show that I use books 1-3 about 
equally as often as The Traveller Book.  Depends on what mood I\'m in, 
strangely enough.
 

> Having never owned either, I haven\'t either.  <g> Actually, I think
> "Intro to.." was published in JTAS or Challenge, I think, so I might
> have read it.

Hmmm.  I don\'t remember it from JTAS.  Might have been Challenge.  Now 
that I\'ve read it, it /is/ a nice piece of work.  I just didn\'t seem to 
need it back when we first started playing.


> Right! Traveller could be anything you wanted...still can.

Yeah.  That\'s just it.  I never had trouble coming up with scenarios for 
Traveller, while in other games I either got into a rut or simply got 
bored and stopped playing.  With thousands of worlds, many alien races 
(some detailed, some less detailed, and still others not even mentioned 
- -- and thus open for your creation!), any tech level you can imagine, and 
everything else available to you, there really is no end to the adventure 
possible with Traveller.  No matter what the size of your Traveller 
collection. :)


> When I bought Supplement 3 I\'d never seen a map.  It provided a
> *wonderful* playground that I could do with what I wanted.  I\'d
> developed several star systems by then and just integrated them into
> the Spinward Marches.  Those were the days my friend!

:)  Yes, indeed.  


> >But there still wasn\'t an Imperium. 
> 
> Actually, I started seeing it referred to in JTAS, and Book 5 (High
> Guard) actually *assumed* some sort of remote centralized government.
> I think they were calling it the Imperium even then.

I\'m sorry, I should have been more specific. I meant, "There still wasn\'t 
an Imperium in my campaign."  I knew of the Imperium by that time, of 
course.  I just didn\'t know enough about it, and I didn\'t really have 
much interest in changing my already-working setting, at that time.


> I guess mine did too, but we never got too close to the official
> history.  Remember how we all felt when WAR! splashed across the JTAS
> cover?  <g> It was very exciting, but my games never got involved in
> the 5th Frontier War...and we skipped the rebellion, the civil war,
> and the V\'thing in their entirety.

We did something similar to that.  We played in the Rebellion when MT came 
out...until we decided the setting, while undeniably exciting for many 
people, wasn\'t for us.  So we went back to CT, and the universe that had 
grown up around our characters through the years.  

Like yours, ours wasn\'t a truly canonical version of the CT universe.  The 
Imperium was almost completely uncaring.  It was an entity capable of 
producing overwhelming force whenever it felt like it...which was usually 
in wars that most of the population felt were unecessary and petty; the 
result of the Imperial nobility\'s hubris.  

Speaking of the nobility, Strephon and the rest of the nobility were off 
in the background somewhere, feasting and piddling their lives away when 
not involved in something horrendously wasteful like war.  So, they really 
didn\'t enter into the picture. More important to the characters were the 
local governments, the overpowering MegaCorps, the super-rich/powerful, 
pirates, and organized criminals.  

Or, in our less-ambitious campaigns, the most important things all 
happened on one planet, and concerned ordinary people affected by their 
neighbors and rivals.

Oh!  This reminds me of a question I wanted to ask of those who refereed 
more than one campaign (I know some of the folks have run the same 
campaign since the beginning):  How much continuity, if any, was there 
between your campaigns?  Did previous characters\' exploits affect 
subsequent adventures?  Were previous characters even known about in 
subsequent campaigns?


> Absolutely not!  
> 
> I *loved* the Traveller News, went there first in every issue of JTAS
> and Challenge, but all that was happening in a different universe.  A
> similar universe, with similar technologies and star systems, but
> still a different one.

Right on.  I read the Traveller News ("Yet another Imperium-wide benefit 
of membership in the Travellers\' Aid Society") to the players each time 
I received my new issue.  It was an on-going story we all followed, but 
only rarely did any of those events happen in my universe.


> Give me the rules!  I\'ll come up with the setting!  Ok, you can give
> me the setting too..just make it easy to separate the two.  <g>

I\'m all for a strong setting with tons and tons of background information 
detailed to the last chromosome of each Alien.  Just, please, make it all 
separate from the game mechanics.

- -Joe
