    'index' => 'ae393',
    'topic' => 'Taking the Hand out of Hand-Computers',
    'body' => 'Yo People,
  Joe Walsh asked some leading questions over on TML which
quickly lead to a thread that rapidly diverged. I\'d like
to bring this back to the quiet civility of XBOAT and the
original point.

Joe Walsh asks a number of questions about hand computers:
Physical:
>Are they notebook-sized?

User Interfaces:
>you do something similar to flipping a page to get it to 
>display the next page?  Or do you say, "flip page?"  
>Would you say the display is very much like ink-and-paper
>in the way it looks, or is it more like a LCD?  

External Interfaces:
>Can they download information from afar, or do they need
>a physical link to the computer being accessed? If the former,
>can they be used as communicators?  Can you link them together
>into a temporary network, allowing every user to see what is
>on some sort of shared display, which they can all interact
>with?  What sort of range do they have?

  Physical was interestingly discussed on TML, mainly around
the (wierd) ideas of flexible computers. What I\'d like to
expound upon is ideas around the user interface.

  Lets try to get away from the "box with buttons" idea. There
are better ways but lets, for the moment, think of our "hand
computer" as a pair of glasses. They sit on the bridge of
your nose not merely correcting vision but giving you the equivalent
of a "heads up display". This can be adjusted from completely
transparent to opaque depending on user preference and activity
(eg sitting at a campfire or driving a air/raft).
  Now, go further. Most conventional HUDs are static. Ie. they
project what they project independant of the attitude of the
head. However why not tie it into where your head is pointing?
(There are several ways to do this I won\'t bore you with.) So
when you look right, you see more screen. Same for up, down,
etc. The size of your virtual HUD grows further.
  Even more so, the corelation between head movement and screen
scrolling doesn\'t have to stop there. Just as a small movement
with a mouse produced a large movement across a computer screen,
moving your head 20 degrees to the right might rotate your
virtual display 40, 60 or 80 degrees, depending on sensativity
settings. (Cherryh\'s battledress works like this.) Thus your
virtual bubble world ends up being a sphere bigger than 360
degrees around (the maths gets a bit wierd, but there _are_
equations).
  With me so far? Next step.
  As the computer is sitting on your face, it has a pretty good
view of your eyes. It can tell exactly where you are looking.
If it wants to display a mouse-like cursor on the screen it can
put it just where you look (gee, I _really_ wish mine did that).
Not only that but since the angle of your eyes is slightly
different depending on how "deep" you are looking than it can
also not only detect direction but depth as well. Thus you have
a 3D "mouse".
  A lot of human non-verbal communication is done through facial
expression. We have quite developed muscles there for a wide
variety of nuances. Your Fabulous Facial Friend ("hand" computer)
can pick up on these. As simple as using different squints to
"right or left click the mouse" up to rather more complicated UI
interactions our immersion in present technology prevents us from
even guessing.
  And for my finale...
  I\'m an old keyboard jock. Mice are grand but try typing in this
article with one. Even with "Expression Entry" I still anticipate
the utility of keyboard-ish manual entry. After all, no matter how
versitile our faces are, our hands are more so.
  So far we have just looked at our "Eye Computers" looking in.
Well there is no reason they can\'t look out just as effectively.
They should be able to determine the exact attitude and placement
of your hands as effectively as your pupils. Say then that in your
virtual HUD a "keyboard" is displayed along with analoges of
your hands. You can then easily "type". (Wasn\'t there a scene like
this in Jonny Mnemonic?)
  Not only that but the keyboard is infinately versitile. You can
add keys, split the keyboard in ergonomic ways, and add bits all
over your virtual environment.
  Similarly the ear-rests can catch the vibrations of your skull
as you sub-vocalise and interpret that as further input for those
even too lazy to use the virtual keyboard...


  So lets wrap up with a bit of colour (and leave external interfaces
for another day)...

  Sid Viscous walks back from the customs house to his ship. He
stops in a park to check out the forms he\'s uploaded. He unfolds
his "hand" computer and places it on his nose. He closes his eyes
briefly and slowly opens them, activating the display to full
opacity. A number of textured portals litter his viewing area.
With a gesture he sweeps them off to his "sides". "Search by
recent", he mutters and a list of the more recently modified
data appears. Glancing and clicking he brings up the recently
uploaded customs lists.
  Grabbing one of the forms he drags it larger and a 3D display
starts explaining the form and its uses. Sid, however, has seen
this many times and, a few blinks later has axed the 3D playback
and is left with the textual representation of the regulations.
As his eyes scan down the document it scrolls more into view.
With various lip gestures he marks places of interest in the
hyper-texed fine print.
  With another eye-gesture he minimises the display and presses
a special "function button" that brings up his ship\'s manifest.
Eye flicking through this he eye-circles sections, and eye-drags
them to bits around on the desktop.
  When he is done with this he re-activates the form and drops
the info into requisite spots. One, however, red-lights, requesting
additional clarification on the containers he has entered as
"footware". He knows the Yasidians have an ankle taboo and that
the sandals he is importing are rather risque\' but local standards
and subject to strict government controls he had hoped to avoid.
  He ponders how he is to fill in this particular section as
a wrong answer could be costly and endanger his lisence. After some
time he is suddenly surrounded by large portable densiometers
soaring on vast pennons through the waif like atmosphere of a
gas giant. His "screen saver" has activated.
  Pulling himself together he dismisses the densiometers (which
flap bashfully behind activated panels) and start calling up
local dictionary translators. They have no real on-line services
outside of customs so he has to rely on data uploaded from there.
He drags screens around and flicks his eyes over definitions trying
to find one that adequately describes his cargo yet doesn\'t trigger
any legal warnings.
  His workspace quickly becomes cluttered and expands from 90
degrees to 180 and up to 270. He ties in several repeated actions
to facial macros and tries to organise his data.
  Suddenly the whole workspace shudders and he feels a heavy
pressure on his shoulder. Closing his eyes and rapidly opening
them set ths computer back to transparent mode. He blinks
repeatedly at an old gentleman poking him with a stick.
  "Are you all right there son? Thought you were having a bit
of a fit. You have to watch the UV around here. Good day, so."
The old mans wanders off in one direction and Sid goes in the
other. There is a Traveller\'s Aid Society around here somewhere.
They might have better dictionaries or old-hands who know the
ropes...



Jo
