    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ae398',
    'body' => 'In somewhere mysterious you write:

>   As the computer is sitting on your face, it has a pretty good
> view of your eyes. It can tell exactly where you are looking.
> If it wants to display a mouse-like cursor on the screen it can
> put it just where you look (gee, I _really_ wish mine did that).
> Not only that but since the angle of your eyes is slightly
> different depending on how "deep" you are looking than it can
> also not only detect direction but depth as well. Thus you have
> a 3D "mouse".

There *are* limits to this. You see, vision *requires* constant
movements of the eyes. If your eyes don\'t move you can\'t see anything.
So a visual "mouse" has a *lot* of "jitter".

>   I\'m an old keyboard jock. Mice are grand but try typing in this
> article with one. Even with "Expression Entry" I still anticipate
> the utility of keyboard-ish manual entry. After all, no matter how
> versitile our faces are, our hands are more so.

Check out the entry system severely handicapped people like Stephen
Hawking use (there was an artical about it in byte about 10 years back.
It uses a set of icons and as you select them they change. They\'re
organized such that it takes *very* few icon choices to get to a word
or phrase. That\'s how Hawking, using something *considerably* less
useful that a mouse can speak in almost real time. Anything that fast
can be made faster with the sort of display you are talking about.
Especially since you\'ll start "memorizing" the movements required to
get common words and phrases, just like a typist can think "the" and
have his fingers hit the proper keys in the proper sequence.

>   So far we have just looked at our "Eye Computers" looking in.
> Well there is no reason they can\'t look out just as effectively.
> They should be able to determine the exact attitude and placement
> of your hands as effectively as your pupils. Say then that in your
> virtual HUD a "keyboard" is displayed along with analoges of
> your hands. You can then easily "type". (Wasn\'t there a scene like
> this in Jonny Mnemonic?)

Actually, the standard keyboard is *way* sub-optimal. And I\'m not
talking about things like the Dvorak keyboard. Check out what the call
"chording" keyboards. You have a key or two for each finger and
generate characters by using combinations of the keys. They don\'t take
much longer to learn, and they are *faster* once you learn. They can
also be set up to avoid carpal tunnel and the like.

The *most* common chording keyboard is the one used on "braillers".
These are intended to let the blind take notes, and they have six
buttons arranged like the dots of a braille character. There are a
couple of other controls, but I forget what they are. 

You just enter braille direct. You\'d think that there are just 64
possible characters. That\'s only partially true. The "braille alphabet"
you see in encyclopedias is what\'s known as "level 1 braille". Level 2
uses some otherwise unused level 1 characters to modify the meanings of
level 1 chars, giving things like multi character groupings or short
common words. Level 3 braille uses 2 and 3 character sequences to
represent entire words and phrases. 

Or consider the keyboards used by court stenographers. They have only
10 or 12 keys, yet they can transcibe damn near anything (it\'s called
"machine shorthand").

Given the above, there\'s no need to bother displaying a keyboard.
Select "text input" and then just flex your fingers in the right
patterns. You don\'t even have to flex them all that much, just enough
for the sensors in your glove (or attached to your wristband) to pick
up. 

> With various lip gestures he marks places of interest in the
> hyper-texed fine print.

With hyper-text storage and any sort of decent search program (using
even contemporary levels of "AI"), "fine print" becomes a meningless
concept. Instead, if someone is trying to be tricky, they\'ll have to do
it via setting up interrelationships between widely seperated
regulations. But slipping that past any sort of computer analysis
requires that you use a computer & software that are better than the
people you are trying to trick have. And the GCLU (Galactic Civil
Liberties Union) has some *good* people trying to find such things.

Yes, hypertext and computer aided searches may actually bring about the
return of the days when you could *understand* the laws affecting you!

- -- 
