    'from' => 'Christopher Sean Hilton chris@vindaloo.c',
    'body' => 'On Wed, 10 Jul 1996, Joe Walsh wrote:

> The way I see it, our ability to store information has increased 
> dramatically from the distant past you mention to today.  That is, in our 
> distant past there wasn\'t a whole lot of information stored in the first 
> place, so of course not a whole lot of that still exists today.  On the 
> other hand, we store so much of our information today that even in the 
> distant future (barring disasters too horrible to imagine) they will 
> still have a great deal of our accumulated knowledge.
> 

Our ability to store information for short periods of time has increased
by leaps and bounds over the past ten years but noone is thinking of long
term storage. The lifespan of information on magnetic tape is less than 20
years and on optical disk it probably less than 100 years. This is without
regard to data layout and character set encoding which brings up a whole
other set of issues. So even if a CD-ROM would last until 5700~5800 AD it
would be difficult to decipher without a contemporary ASCII table and
printed copy of the CD-ROM data layout books as rosetta stones so to
speak. I think it\'s foolish to assume that we will employ a significant
portion of the earth\'s workforce in the endevour of constantly converting
databases which are meaningless out of context from "obsolete" formats to
"modern" formats every twenty years or so. 

What this means is that _some_ historical data will be saved. A list of
American presidents provided that when we get around to creating one-world
government it\'s not the Japanese that end up with the most influence 8-). 
Land records and trades will be meticulously maintained for as long as we
can buy and sell land. There\'s probably a tonne of stuff that\'s I\'m
missing but the point is that it\'s foolish to think that it will be
possible to look up a twentieth century individual\'s credit rating and
local buying habits more than 20 years after his death even though that
information is meticulously collected, stored and maintained now. Also, 
forget this information storage if there\'s a short war to interrupt this 
"golden age" of information in which we live. Computers and information 
have become so important that they will certainly be first line targets 
in the next war.

Chris
