    'day' => '11',
    'body' => 'Eris raises the question...

>...and that raises the question:  Why did the "long night" last
> over a thousand years?
> 

     Probably because the books said so...;-)  Actually, the term \'Long 
Night\' is mostly  Cleon-ist propoganda, and refers mostly to the lack 
of a centralized Government, most places did not fall into barbarism.

     But, here\'s an idea...The long night was mostly an economic 
phenomenon, brought about by two major factors...the long supression 
of technology by the Vilani, and the over heated, over rapid 
expansion of the Rule of Man.

      The former guaranteed that the majority of worlds were dependent
upon imports from select high tech planets for a large amount of
their infrastructure.  This is well in line with the conservative,
monopolistic practices of the Vilani. Thus very few worlds had the
ability to maintain their current tech level (meaning interstellar
travel), and since knowledge was so supressed by the Vilani, even
the ability to recreate the tech was not there.  These planets would
have had to go through the equivalent of the Renaissance, the
Enlightenment, and the Industrial age, all over again to get back to
where they were.

     The Terran rule probably made things worse.  The rapid expansion 
probably stretched and broke what infrastructure was there..again, 
leading to significant dependence on technological imports.

     When the economy collapsed, everyone drew back to smaller and 
smaller spheres of influence. Star travel never died out, but trade 
was economically unviable in many areas. These areas were never quite 
lost as much as ignored.

     With economic collapse, as surely as summer follows spring, comes 
warfare...fighting between the remaining starfaring groups probably 
destroyed even more of the advanced technological base.

     This could well have led to a rather isolationist viewpoint on many 
many of the worlds involved, again supressing interstellar trade 
and travel.

     With the combination of a lack of technical resources, the lack of 
knowledge, and isolationist policies, it\'s not hard to figure that 
the Long Night would fall.

     Why did this state persist for a thousand years? I dunno...I\'d be 
more likely to think of it in terms of a few hundred, unless by sheer 
fortuitous luck, no one in the entire known universe with the drive, 
and resources of Cleon I existed until he did.
Bruce Johnson
Information Technology/College of Pharmacy
The University of Arizona
johnson@tonic.pharm.arizona.edu 


As if this place HAD any opinions...
