Last night I get the official timeline from TNE and calculated the
"equivalent" times in Earth-history.  I.E. in 1117 the Imperium is 1117
years old.  1117 before 1996AD is 879AD.  Take an example from "local
history": 879 is approx the time that Kenneth MacAlpine unified Scotland.
How many people, even here, know that, or care?  At high school history
lessons skimmed over everything before the industrial revolution (:-()
giving only the broadest strokes before getting to the "relevant" stuff.  I
would guess that education in the Imperium would have a similar bias towards
"recent" events, and every planet would have its own spin on what the events
meant.  The foundation of the Imperium would surely be a semi-legendary
event to most people, perhaps like the origins of China to modern people
living there.   I think that the average Imperial citizen might view the
rise of Terra and its conquest of the Ziru Sirka in much the same way as we
view the arrival in Greece of certain iron-armed tribes from the steppes:
very important to the origins of our culture but not really relevant nowadays.

I agree that records would survive into the far future, but I\'m not sure how
complete they would be.  For example, how many history books will make it
onto CD, and how many of those will eventually make it onto holo-cube and
subsequent media? How many scholars will dedicate their careers to studying
the history of pre-fusion Terra?  On Earth itself people might know (for
example) that their was once a great country called the United States, and
that it had presidents and that one was called Kennedy, but I would guess
that practically no-one would know which order the presidents served or what
they did, just as very few people know which order the pharoahs ruled in.
On other imperial planets people might be aware that there was once a world
called Terra (barbaric name!) and that much imperial culture was orginally
derived from there, and that the Terrans claimed to be the original humans:
I wonder if they would be aware of much more.  But think of the
opportunities for future Cecil B DeMilles - "Thrill as Neil Armstrong, his
glamourous sidekick Valentina and the heroic soldiers of Nasa battle against
viscious Aslan raiders on the sands of ancient Luna" (subtitles in Anglic) :-)

Jamie


