    'body' => 'In somewhere mysterious you write:

> In somewhere American Leonard Erickson writes:
>
>>Check out the entry system severely handicapped people like Stephen
>>Hawking use
>   101 keys, 10 keys, 1 key, it is still a keyboard, In my description I
> said you basically have programable "active regions" you can
> put anywhere. I\'d call it a keyboard so my players can relate to it.
> In practice it can be anything you want.

I intend to track down a machine readable listing of the level 3
braille standard one of these days. I suspect that it will be a close
to optimal text encoding system.... :-)

>>Check out what the call "chording" keyboards.
>   Why stop there? One player wanted his "hand computer" configured
> so that you "typed" using intricate spell-weaving type gestures :-).

Ah, you have a budding technomage. :-)

>>Given the above, there\'s no need to bother displaying a keyboard.
>>Select "text input" and then just flex your fingers in the right
>>patterns. You don\'t even have to flex them all that much, just enough
>>for the sensors in your glove (or attached to your wristband) to pick up. 
>   Um, that\'s the end result of the configurability I postulate.
> In case you didn\'t notice I\'m not talking about anything as primitive as
> a glove either. One optical sensor should do the trick.

Only if it\'s an imaging sensor. Simpler (and much cheaper and more
reliable) sensors can detect things like mucle contractions or joint
flexes. I think tension of tendons would work well as that\'s
proportional to the flexing of the fingers, and can be easily measured
at the wrist.

>>With hyper-text storage and any sort of decent search program (using
>>even contemporary levels of "AI"), "fine print" becomes a meningless
>>concept.
>   Oh, ho, ho, ho! Not a chance. "Fine print" just takes on a new meaning.
> Take airline reservation systems. Once they were computerised everyone
> thought that we now were going to have fair and equal chances for any
> airline to get tickets. Then some airlines started changing their departure
> times by a few minutes in different directions so that the search software
> put them on the top of the list for commonly used search engines.

Won\'t help them with me. Last time I used the OAG, I selected start and
end points, then the date of departure and the *prices*. I\'m *real*
flexible on time, and it was a "one hop" flight. :-)

But I meant "fine print" in the sense of "concealing" info.

>>Yes, hypertext and computer aided searches may actually bring about the
>>return of the days when you could *understand* the laws affecting you!
>   Laws will always complexify themselves to the point where you need
> professionals to interpret them. Ever since good old Hamurabi carved
> that stele there have been lawyers. There always will be.
>   Hypertext contains no magical solution. If you make it long enough and
> with enough cross references you will need a professional to interpret.
> It is just that it allows you to express much more complicated laws than
> cuneiform.

I suspect that we\'ll reach the situation described in an Analog story.
Everyone will have their personal AI, and it\'ll download the local laws
as you enter the jurisdiction. Then it\'ll advise you on what you need
to worry about.

Lawyers and laws haven\'t gotten a lot of attention from computer
science types yet. But it turns out that the notation used for computer
langauge syntax diagrams works *very* well for laws. And the result is
both more compact and easier to understand. 

Lexical analysis is going to make things *very* different. It\'s a
relatively new tool, and hasn\'t (yet) been applied in this area. 

As for plot ideas, how about a "practical joke" by a "friend". He loads
a program into your "glasses" that does to your vision and hearing what
things like "jive" and "valspeak" do to text.

You could get into a *lot* of trouble before you took off the glasses.
