    'day' => '12',
    'from' => 'hdhale@smtpgate.read.tasc.com',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ae426',
    'body' => 'Greetings all,

   I overheard in interesting conversation the other day while sitting in a
local theater waiting for the movie ``Independence Day`` to start (by
the way, I highly recommend it--it\'s not ``Sense and Sensibility``, but
then it doesn\'t try to be--it is vaguely reminiscent of the Star Wars trilogy,
however).

   A person brought up the name Clark Cable during a conversation.  The
other said, ``oh yeah, he was an actor, wasn\'t he?``

   In a conversation with my sister a few years ago, I brought up the
name Elton John.  She, being ten years younger than me, had no idea
who he was.

   Information and historical data will no doubt be available in quantity
about 20th century Earth in the 58th century.  The real question is, will
anyone care, or will certain myths be accepted as fact.

   We know from Survival Margin that Strephon quoted Lincoln, so at
least some American influence continues on.  The Third Imperium is
described as having a substantial middle-class, and that Imperial culture
is similar to ``that of late 20th century America`` (then again we should
remember that the authors of Traveller are late 20th century Americans,
so we shouldn\'t be too surprised).

   One twist that is part of Traveller canon involves the worship by
a certain Solomani religious sect, of Elvis Presley.  While probably just
thrown in for comic relief, remember that there really *is* a group
currently in existence that calls itself ``The Church of Elvis``, in which
believers treat Elvis Presley as a holy man (these people claim to be
nominally Christian).

   Now on to Jamie Young\'s comments:

>Last night I get the official time line from TNE and calculated the
>"equivalent" times in Earth-history.  I.E. in 1117 the Imperium is 1117
>years old.  1117 before 1996AD is 879AD.  Take an example from
>"local history": 879 is approx the time that Kenneth MacAlpine unified
>Scotland.
>
>How many people, even here, know that, or care?

   Good point.  It is likely that the average Imperial citizen doesn\'t know
Lincoln from Washington.  Someone with `History-1` might know that
they were great American Presidents, someone with `History-2` might
also know that Washington was the first U.S. president (some with
History-7 would know that John Hancock was technically the first
president, but he was President of the Continental Congress), and that
Lincoln was President during something called ``The American Civil
War``, which they might wrongly conclude was similar to the Imperial
Civil War and that characters such as Lee and Jefferson Davis were
generals trying to seize the Presidency from Lincoln.  You get the idea.

>I would guess that education in the Imperium would have a similar bias
>towards "recent" events, and every planet would have its own spin on
>what the events meant.  

   While certain facts was be consistent because to the influence of
Imperial culture, it is likely that if you want to study American history
(or British history, etc.) you would have to do your own independent
studies, or take an Ancient History course down at the local university.

>How many scholars will dedicate their careers to studying the history
>of pre-fusion Terra?  

   Probably large numbers of them, just as there as large numbers of
Egyptologists today.  Rancorous debates would probably take place
between Imperial and Solomani ``Terraology`` scholars about the causes
of World War II, what country baseball originated in, controversial 
interpretations and translations of ancient Terran texts (remember folks,
it is very unlikely that the people who speak Galactic English are
speaking the Queen\'s English--Lord knows if anyone still speaks Italian
in any form), etc.

   And Stewart Eyres writes:

>Anyone remember Zaphod Beeblebrox (sp?) trying to use the Heart of
>Gold\'s optical controls?

   Do I sense a Douglas Adams reference here?  Good stuff.

>Canon says that the TC grew out of the United Worlds, which itself
>grew out of the UN.  There is a Challenge adventure (I forget which
>Challenge, or the adventure\'s title) about an early Terran explorer who
>some how survives to the 57th Century, and her experience of the
>TC was that it was fairly liberal - the racist ideals of the Solomani
>(who claim her and her period of history as role models) disgust her.

   Rachel Strider was her name.  As I recall, the ending of the adventure
left it open as to whether she was the real thing or an imposter trying
to embarrass the Solomani government.

>Of course, the hawks in the TC were gaining power, and the TC
>probably became a military-inclined nation shortly after she left the
>scene

   Hundreds of years of war created a ``warrior elite`` who were
responsible for the prosecution of the war.  Looked on and idolized as
heroes, no doubt, unfortunately one of them decided that the
Confederation government had no business treating the Vilani Imperium
as spoils of war, and decided to instigate a coup....

>Doesn\'t the latest Traveller Chronicle cover this area?

   The latest Traveller Chronicle (#10) covers primarily New Era material
for the Solomani Rim (the Terran Republic), though there are references
to pre-Collapse history.  The next couple of issues of Traveller Chronicle
should go into more depth about pre-Collapse matters.

>No way! Let me tell you a little secret - the US of A doesn\'t exist in the
>58th century!  Unless your citizen comes from Terra, this knowledge is
>going to be entirely unknown, and even then it would probably be
>relatively common knowledge for North American citizens.

   Nor does the UK, at least as we known it.  There are administrative
districts called `England`, `Scotland`, etc. but they exist as a way to
divide the planet for governing purposes only.  There are probably
cultural regions, where tourists can gawk at ``Californians`` and
``Germans`` (who probably aren\'t those things any more than residents
of Rome are Ancient Romans), but that\'s as close as you\'re going to get
to being home.

>Don\'t underestimate the average man\'s ignorance of history.

   You\'re comments about Washington and Lincoln and Kennedy prove
the point I was making about Clark Cable and Elton John above.

   BTW, President Kennedy owned the rocking chair--he had a bad back
and the chair helped.  Lincoln freed the slaves (actually Union troops and
the slaves themselves did the real work, but you get the idea).

   I wonder how many Americans can name even three UK Prime
Ministers?  We\'ll worry about the royals later....

>How many average people can name Roman Emperors?  Caeser? Not a
>name, but a title (although I think the distinction was a little blurred
>then).  

   Actually Caesar, and it was both a name and a title (as was
Augustus).  The original Caesar was of course Julius.  Later on during
the Empire it became a title.

   Of course I know much of the above because I was a History major
in college.  Others may not know as much.

Regards,

Harold
