    'from' => 'Christopher Sean Hilton chris@vindaloo.c',
    'body' => 'On Fri, 12 Jul 1996 gsw@aloft.att.com wrote:

> Consider also how much information can fit in just a single CD-ROM
> today, and DVDs are expanding this. How soon will it be before every
> "important" book ever written will fit on a single optical disk?
> I don\'t know how long a CD-ROM will last (it\'s probably longer than
> 100 years if its shrink-wrapped :-), but all that it takes is for
> somebody to reprint it every so often. Even if you have to spend
> some time figuring out a disk format from 200 years ago (which isn\'t
> really *that* hard), the knowledge from one disk would be worth it.
> 

The problem isn\'t the density of the data storage medium it\'s the 
lifespan before that medium is unreadable. The magnetic domains in 
computer tapes "print-through" from layer to layer over time. After 
fifteen to twenty years the amount of "signal" from print-through is 
higher than the noise threshold on the tape. This makes it difficult and 
expensive to read the tape and extract the data from it. This isn\'t a 
problem if you know what\'s on each tape because you can pick and choose 
which tapes to process. But after you\'re gone and the only thing left is 
a box of mag-tapes...

The second problem is data format and it\'s even bigger. In many cases 
tape is easier in this regard because it\'s a serial stream of "words" 
recorded across the tape surface. CD-ROM is harder because it\'s a serial 
stream of bits so the wordsize information is encoded in the CD-ROM 
reader which certainly won\'t exist n * 10^3 years from now. 

Think of it this way. In the year 5700 AD any CD is going to be a 
curious little disk with a very long serial bit stream encoded on a 
piece of aluminum sandwiched between two layers of acrylic plastic. No offense to 
anyones musical taste but without the label and/or a CD-DA/ROM reader, 
how do you tell the difference between "Frampton comes alive" and 
"Project Gutenburg"? Even if they only encoded data on CD-ROM how do you 
tell the difference between "Project Gutenburg" and "Northbrook Vehicle 
taxes assed - 1996"

When you layer on top of this the fact that every CD-ROM that\'s pressed 
isn\'t going to survive from now until the 5th frontier you\'ve got to 
admit that alot of information is going to be lost. 

Now don\'t forget that this assumes that the storage method (CD-ROM/DA 
is just an example) doesn\'t suffer from some sort of bit rot over time 
like magnetic tape does. 

Chris
