    'from' => 'gsw@aloft.att.com',
    'body' => 'On Saturday, July 13, Christopher Sean Hilton <chris@vindaloo.com> wrote:

> The problem isn\'t the density of the data storage medium it\'s the 
> lifespan before that medium is unreadable. [ ... ]

> The second problem is data format and it\'s even bigger. [ ... ]

> When you layer on top of this the fact that every CD-ROM that\'s pressed 
> isn\'t going to survive from now until the 5th frontier you\'ve got to 
> admit that alot of information is going to be lost. 

Of course, a great deal of information will be lost. The point is
that a great deal of information, especially important things like
great literary works and "accumulated knowledge", will not be lost.

High-density media will virtually guarantee that *somebody* will
take the time to keep a current copy of this data. Also, it makes
it worth your while to take the time to decode old media if there
was a lapse for some reason. Also, if there is lapse (for example
due to a war), people will likely be taking time *afterwards* to
recover a great deal of this "lost information", so the format of
the data will be known anyway.

However, even if you needed to decode a 20th century CD-ROM which
was somehow intact (frozen in dry ice?), it really would not be
*that* hard to do. Analysis under a microscope makes it obvious
that the data is stored as "pits" in a circular fashion. The data
structure can easily be detected by looking for patterns. Even
the 8-bit ASCII character set can be easily determined using some
simple cryptographic methods (the same goes for compressed data,
images, etc). So if you had a copy of Grolier\'s Encyclopedia, you
can at least figure out what *data* is on it. What you do with a
3700-year-old copy of Windows 95 is your problem, though. :-) :-)

