    'topic' => ' Earth (lots of questions)',
    'body' => 'On Sat, 13 Jul 1996, Leonard Erickson wrote:

> In somewhere mysterious you write:
> 
> > It depends on the storage format of the original material and the 
> > cost that the vendor of the new information system assigns to data 
> > conversion. It also depend on whether or not the customer is willing to 
> > pay the vendor\'s price. This is highly variable. The hospital that I used 
> > to work for had medical records dating back to 1826. They had on-line 
> > information dating back to 1987. The online data is simple to convert so 
> > it stays but the paper information is purged once it\'s confirmed that 
> > the the patient has died and the info is no longer needed. This is the 
> > typical case.
> 
> I bet you that they hold the data until *years* after the patient dies.
> If not, they will, first time there\'s a lawsuit and they can\'t produce
> the records.
> 

Your right here MedicoLegal had some say in how long the information 
was kept after the patient had died. I think it was in the 
neighborhood of seven years because after that time it was difficult 
if not near impossible to sue the hospital. The amount of time 
doesn\'t matter. The point is that people stayed at our facility in 
1826 but no-one there could tell you anything about them because in 
nearly eveyone\'s opinion that information was without value and but it 
cost\'s money (warehouse space) to keep and maintain. 

> >> But now you know why businesses are so strong on hardcopy records.
> >
> > Hardcopy records are _currently_ difficult to save. In many cases they 
> > are not stored on acid free paper so the storage medium itself is 
> > degrading (like magnetic tapes).
> 
> All too true. But businesses count microfilm as "hardcopy". I have a
> friend whose job used to be microfilming bank records all day long. And
> this was for a medium size "local" bank.

This is true too but how long does information on microfilm last before 
it has to put on another media. Will microfilm last 3700 years or will 
someone have to take the volumes of data that on it and convert it to 
something else every couple of hundred years. Going back to my hospital 
keeping the medical records of people who attended in 1899 isn\'t 
necessary because: They\'re not going to sue and the art of medicine was 
so primitive back then that we don\'t think that we are going to learn 
anything from it. Given that it cost $25.00 / square foot for warehouse 
space (cool and dry to reduce degradation) the business decision is to 
throw that information away. This is model that I think most things will 
go by. It\'s harder to envision this happening to the government and 
historical information but that\'s because over our lifetime the 
Government of the United States is a very stable entity and will perceive 
some value in maintaining its history. Some time after that changes, some 
time after the U.S. Government goes away by whatever means the 
details of the history of this regime will be lost. In 3700 years 
historical scholars will be able to figure out that the United States 
existed and who the president was in 1963. But this information won\'t be 
required reading for every Imperial Citizen and it won\'t be the easiest 
information to find either.

Chris
