Although it\'s not much to go on, there is some evidence that Terran culture
will continue to have a major influence on Imperial culture as a whole.  The
official language of the Imperium, and one that is spoken and understood by
all starfarers (and a majority of it\'s citizens, at least according to all
available evidence) is "Galanglic" - a descendant of modern English.

How close Galanglic is to English is debatable, but from the available
evidence (not much, unfortunately) modern English is at least as
understandable to Imperials as Chaucer is to present-day readers.

> 150 years ago Great Britain was THE dominant
> world power, with perhaps greater (certainly more direct) sway over
> the world than the US has now.  Now we are a small, reasonably
> successful island state, with an international importance that probably
> owes more to our past than our present, and a lot of mad cows.

On the other hand, Great Britain has had a large influence on the cultural
background of all of the English-speaking countries of the world.
Shakespeare, Dickens, Conan-Doyle, Gilbert and Sullivan.  The King James
version of the bible, even.   By the time of the Imperium, perhaps old
Terran works will be more a matter of curiosity (and modern
"interpretations") than popular culture - on the other hand, there are
several different copies of Beowulf in print right now!

It\'s a known fact that at least some of CS Lewis\' works survive into the
world of Traveller - because that\'s the origin of the term "Aslan" for a
certain race of aliens.  I can\'t imagine that Tolkien (for example), will
ever go out of print, and I\'m sure that others can think of a long list of
other works that will remain in print for as long as there are people to
read them.  While perhaps not so politically important, culturally the
influence extends as far as the English language.

So, I can see a lot of reason for there to be influences from current
popular culture - on the other hand, I think those influences should be
subtle and not overdone (and it\'s very easy to over-do this).


