>>curriculum in Millue 0, or even later.  Of course, by the time period of
>>Classic Traveller, much of that history has probably been cut out of the
>>curriculum, to make room for the study of all those Emperors of the Flag.

I don\'t think pre-starfaring Terra would be taught as "history\'" at all. It
would
be taught as an entirely different subject, the 57thC equivilent of Classics
or Antiquities, perhaps even Archeology.
What is taught as history tends to break down into three major groupings:
    1) Local history - i.e. a child on Regina will learn of the colonisation of
Regina, the development of the colony, how it\'s social systems evolved etc.
    2) Case studies - These are studies of how other cultures have dealt with
common problems. Thus in high school in New Zealand I studied the history
of Ireland as a case study in conflict.
    3) Background history - This is basically local history given a deeper and
wider coverage. Thus our Regina school child might learn of the colonisation
of the Spinward Marches, the development of the Imperium, the social changes
brought about by the Civil War etc.

Almost all of what is taught before tertiary level is either local history or
case studies. Obviously, unless the history is being taught on or near
Terra, local history will not concern itself with Terra. Case studies tend
to restrict themsleves to the previous 100-200 years so as to remain
culturally relevant.

So this leaves only background history to concern itself with 20thC Terra.
However I don\'t think it would. Background history concentrates on how
past trends have influenced modern culture. The Long Night provides a
logical break, much as the fall of the Western Roman Empire does now
to act as a starting point for History.

>I would still argue that any histories of Terra taught to non-specialists
>would concentrate on Terra\'s role after first contact, and would be unlikely
>to delve into the early presidents of one of its nations (which is where
>this thread started).  Of course, future history is probably likely to prove
>us all wrong. ("Few 20th century analysts could have predicted the
>amazing rise to world domination of the Glorious Belgian Empire, and
>the rapid Belgification of global culture..")

Here I disagree. While I would think that the study of 20thC Terra (and the
Terran Confederation, Rule of Man and Ziru Sirka) would not be classified
as history. I think 19thC and 20thC Terra would be quite a popular period
to cover. Primarily because of the rapid rate of change during this period. One
only has to look at the rate of technological change, from TL3 to TL8 in
200 years whereas the Imperium has only managed from TL12 to TL15 in
over 1000 years.

I also think that 20thC Terran history would be widely though very very
superficially know in the 57thC. Since it would not be history as such, it would
be free from the political overtones that invariably go with "history". It would
have become as much a part of their pop culture as classical Greece and
Rome have of ours (Can just see the holo series now "The legendary
adventures of J.F.K." or even "Maggie Thatcher, Warrior Princess").

  Andrew etc.
