    'index' => 'ae487',
    'body' => 'Hugh wrote some very interesting stuff yesterday about
archivists/librarians refreshing archives, and computer stuff in
general. As a digital archivist (among other things) I wholeheartedly
concur in principle, although the eventual data storage capacities and
media are anyone\'s wild guess, especially speculations beyond the next
fifty or so years.
But I refer you all to todays Guardian newspaper (Thursday July 18 1996)
in England, which carries a big front page article \'From cradle to grave
on memory chip\' . Basically the article reports on the Soul Catcher 2025
team based at British Telecom\'s Martlesham Heath laboratories near
Ipswich (in Suffolk, England). Time prevents me from repeating it all
but suffice it to say that a kind of Dennis Potter \'Cold Lazarus\'
scenario (which surely prompted this article\'s appearance, the play just
recently having been shown on UK terrestrial channels)  where the entire
lives of people are put on 10 million megabyte chips with some
(unspecified) means of playback so that other users experience it as if
it were their own memory blah blah etc. Benefits listed are: advancement
over \'crude\' speech and writing communication forms, easier teaching
methods, enhanced memories for sufferers of Alzheimer\'s Disease, and
less possibility of thieves & rapists escaping justice if a record of
the crime was stored in a witness\'s/victim\'s chip.

Have to rush off now, work calls, but perhaps this is food for thought?
Perhaps you\'ve heard it all before.... :-)

Paul

P.S. Please allow me to introduce myself later, rather late I know, but
I hope you\'ll overlook the impoliteness and get stuck into the chatter.
