 >While I don\'t have a definitive answer, I rather suspect that microfilm
 >is *at least* as durable as paper, if not more so.

     Um, well...no.  It\'s not.  Not by a long shot.  I work at a data
center that, among other things, does COM (Computer Originated Microfilm
[and fiche]).  We recently got some ten-year-old fiche in to be
duplicated (masters are archived--duplicates are used for everyday
access), and they were almost unusable.  Decayed to the point that they
had to be babied by hand through the duplicator.  We eventually got
decent duplicates, but the quality was very poor.  And that\'s after only
ten years.

 >Given "reasonable" storage conditions, the means of degradation I see
 >as most likely are:
 >
 >1. oxidation (*very* slow, acetate film is damn stable)

     It certainly is--too bad acetate isn\'t used for microfilm or fiche.
It\'s 15-mil (average) polymer (at least, the Kodak film we use--the
Diazo dupe film is slightly thicker).

 >2. migration of dye (the "dye" that the film uses may slowly migrate
 >   over time)

     This isn\'t a problem--the film is old-fashioned silver wet-
processed.  Modern photographic dyes aren\'t used.  We even run our used
chemicals through a silver recovery unit--enough there to be worth the
effort.

 >3. adhesion/bonding (the adjacent pieces of film may adhere if kept in
 >   contact long enough)

     This doesn\'t take very long, depending on the quality of the newly-
made masters.  If they\'re packaged together wet, they stick together
within *minutes*.  If they\'re properly dry, they should be okay for 15
years or so.  It depends on the storage environment.

