One of the *big* problems is that the media only holds those differing
domains for so long. They tend to "blur" around the edges after a
while. Which is why tricks like using DD media for HD are a bad idea.

Another *major* problem is the binder used to hold the ferrite
particles to the plastic. Some of those fail all too easily. A friend
had a BBS that in the early 80s used the floppy drive *heavily* (it was
essentially an online text editor, and the text was stored one line per
128 byte sector). He found that some brands of floppy failed in a
matter of *hours* on his system. He kept one of the worst examples. It
has large patches where you can *see* through the clear plastic because
*all* the coating came off!

Personally, I have a 3.5 few disks that are unreadable because the
media was *glued* to the metal hub, and the glue failed!

> Lack of reading machinery is probably a more
> pressing problem (there are _two_ machines in existence today that 
> can read the 1960 U.S. census data tapes.)  OTOH, if you made a CD-ROM
> out of pure aluminum instead of plastic-and-aluminum it might well
> last for centuries, if not millenia.

It\'s not just the drives. I can find lots of drives that\'ll handle 5.25
DSSD and DSDD media. But the *format* can be a problem. Try finding
software that can let your PC read the disks created by my Model 100
DVI. They are "normal" 5.25 DSDD disks, 40 track, 18 256 byte sectors
per track. But just *try* getting from there to the directory and file
structure. :-)

And forget the *single* density disks. Many of the floppy controllers
out there can\'t read single density anymore. Forget trying to figure
out the format, you can\'t even get the *bits* off the media.

As for the kind of thing you mention, I bet that in 15 years you\'ll
have to hunt to find a ZIP drive.

> If you really want long-term storage, though, carve your words in 
> granite, or put them on baked clay tablets.  Pottery is virtually
> indestructible (OK, it\'ll shatter, but the fragments will stay
> around), unless you physically destroy it (as in, grind to 
> powder.)  Stone tablets, likewise.  

Or just use micro-lithography to copy them onto silicon wafers. At
micron level lithography, you could use a 5x7 character matrix (add one
dot "space" between characters both horizontally and vertically to get
6x8 "cells")  and that gives you a bit over 20 *billion* characters per
cm^2. And they too will endure for a *long* time. And one of the things
that has come out of semiconductor research is the ability to coat
things with a layer of *diamond*. That\'ll protect the surface nicely.

And like your stone tablets, these with last a *long* time.

I\'d arrange a long term archive with some sort of "plates" of something
durable with incised or etched text. They\'d explain how to read the
next level of archives, which would be "microfilm" sized text and
pictures on something like artificial diamond "grown" around the text.
The next level would be the micron level stuff. And if we ever come up
with a *stable* means of storing data more densely than that, we can
have a fourth level. But we *could* do the first three levels now. 

