    'topic' => ' Sand casters and Book Three',
    'body' => 'Daniel <rkdious@ix.netcom.com> wrote:

>I\'m not very clear on how sand casters were ment to be used during book
>three combat?

Book Three? Which version of Traveller are you using?


>Is the sand shot in space to form a shield or is it shot at an enemy
>target to protect against their shots?

IIRC, in Classic Traveller when sandcasters are fired a cannister
full of ablative particles is ejected into space and a cloud of
ablative particles forms (nominally between the defending ship and
the attacking ship). This cloud travels with the defending ship until
that ship changes its vector at which point the cloud either breaks
up or continues along the original vector depending on whether or
not you want to keep track of it on the playing area.

Later versions of the Traveller space combat system change how all of 
this works.


>There is some mention of moving sand during the Movement Phase and there is
>a defensive DM of -3 for every 25mm of sand an enemy shot has to go through.
>But what is the area of effect for a single sand shot?

I used DM -3 per cannister (rightly or wrongly :-). I don\'t recall
what the Traveller game "Mayday" (long out of print) has to say
about all of this.


>Also, if a ship travels through a field of sand does it take damage?

Certainly possible, but I can\'t find a rule about this in CT. So as 
far as the rules are concerned, it\'s probably safe to ignore (unless, 
of course, it lead the players into an interesting adventure -- in 
which case, have at it!).


Cheers,
     David
